Parent: position: relative
Child: position: absolute
Behavior

When a child element has position: absolute, it positions itself relative to the nearest positioned ancestor.

A positioned ancestor means any parent with:

position: relative
position: absolute
position: fixed
position: sticky

Since the parent has position: relative, the child will use that parent as its reference point.

Example
<div class="parent">
  <div class="child"></div>
</div>
.parent {
  position: relative;
  width: 300px;
  height: 300px;
  background: lightblue;
}

.child {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  right: 0;
  width: 50px;
  height: 50px;
  background: red;
}
Result

The child div will appear at the top-right corner of the parent div, not the page.

Visual Explanation
Parent (relative)
┌────────────────────┐
│                    │
│                    │
│              ■     │  <- child (absolute)
│                    │
│                    │
└────────────────────┘

The child is positioned inside the parent box.

What if parent was NOT relative?

If the parent had:

position: static (default)

Then the child (absolute) would position itself relative to the viewport or nearest positioned ancestor above it.

So it might go to the top-right of the page instead of the parent.

Interview One-Line Answer

If a parent has position: relative and the child has position: absolute, the child element is positioned relative to the parent container instead of the viewport. The parent acts as the reference point for the child's top, left, right, and bottom values.